  <h1>Privacy Policy for GCal Event/Task Creator</h1>
  <p><strong>Last Updated: June 17, 2026</strong></p>

  <p>This Privacy Policy describes how the browser extension <strong>GCal Event/Task Creator</strong> (also distributed under the name <strong>Schedule Sync</strong>, hereinafter referred to as "the extension" or "we") accesses, processes, stores, and transfers your information. We are committed to protecting your privacy and ensuring your personal schedule data remains secure.</p>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <strong>Key Principle:</strong> GCal Event/Task Creator is entirely <strong>client-side and serverless</strong>. We do not run any developer-owned servers. Your schedule, emails, and credentials never pass through us. All communication is made directly from your browser to Google APIs and the Gemini API.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Information Accessed and Processed</h2>
  <p>The extension accesses and processes your data solely to perform its core features (automatically extracting dates/times and creating calendar events and tasks):</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Active Tab Scraped Text:</strong> The extension reads webpage text or highlighted text selection on Gmail, Outlook, or other browser tabs <em>only</em> when you manually trigger the "Extract from Active Thread" command.</li>
    <li><strong>Uploaded Documents:</strong> The extension parses document text when you drag and drop local files (PDFs, Excel spreadsheets, CSVs, TXT, ICS) into the extension to extract scheduling events.</li>
    <li><strong>Google OAuth Scopes:</strong>
      <ul>
        <li><code>https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events</code> (Google Calendar API): Accessed to read, check for duplicate events, and write scheduled events to your target Google Calendar.</li>
        <li><code>https://www.googleapis.com/auth/tasks</code> (Google Tasks API): Accessed to write checklist tasks and deadline reminders to your Google Tasks account.</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2. Data Storage and Security</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Local Device Storage:</strong> Your configuration preferences and credentials (such as your Gemini API Key, custom Google OAuth Client ID, and Target Calendar ID) are stored locally in your browser's private extension sandbox via <code>chrome.storage.local</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Local Erasure:</strong> You can instantly wipe all stored configuration data and cached OAuth tokens by clicking the "Clear Saved" button in the extension's settings panel. Removing the extension from your browser also permanently deletes all local data.</li>
    <li><strong>Transit Security:</strong> All API communication with Google services (Google Calendar, Google Tasks, and Gemini AI) is executed directly from your browser using secure HTTPS protocols.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>3. Data Sharing and Third-Party Services</h2>
  <p>We do not sell, trade, rent, lease, or share your personal information, scraped webpage text, or calendar events with any third parties.</p>
  <p>To fulfill its AI functionality, the extension makes direct connections to the following external Google endpoints from your browser:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Google APIs (<code>https://www.googleapis.com/*</code>)</strong>: Used to write events to Google Calendar and checklists to Google Tasks.</li>
    <li><strong>Google Cloud Gemini API (<code>https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/*</code>)</strong>: Used to send unstructured text to Google's Gemini models for parsing dates, times, and descriptions. This communication is governed by the Google Cloud Terms of Service.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>4. User Control and Revocation</h2>
  <p>You have full control over your connections and data:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>You can view and clear your local settings in the extension's Settings Panel (⚙️).</li>
    <li>You can revoke the extension's access to your Google Account at any time by visiting your Google Account Security settings under "Third-party apps with account access".</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5. Contact & Support</h2>
